JACKSON Mthembu has launched a R1 million lawsuit against Hlaudi Motsoeneng.ANC chief whip Mthembu has taken legal action for what he says is malicious and defamatory comments by Motsoeneng, the SABC group executive of corporate affairs. Motsoeneng allegedly said in a live TV broadcast last month that Mthembu had attempted to capture him.In the televised briefing, Motsoeneng warned Mthembu to stop making noises about the SABC.After this outburst, Mthembu wrote a letter to Motsoeneng demanding he disclose all the details of the alleged meeting where such attempted &ldquo;capture&rdquo; took place. Motsoeneng refused to retract the statement, and Mthembu is now dragging him to court.In a statement, Mthembu&rsquo;s office said Motsoeneng&rsquo;s claims are unfounded, unsubstantiated and blatantly false.It said the accusations were intended to attack the character of the chief whip and were clearly designed to threaten and blackmail him and the ANC in Parliament into silence, with the hope that the inquiry into the SABC would be abandoned.Motsoeneng&rsquo;s lawyer, Zola Majavu, said he had not received court papers and would not be able to comment.In the court papers, according to Mthembu&rsquo;s statement, he is demanding that Motsoeneng:pay a sum of R1 millionissue an unconditional public apology for the injury caused to the chief whip&rsquo;s namepay the legal costs.